SN  - 2375-5334
VO  - 
VL  - 
JA  - 2011 IEEE Virtual Reality Conference
Y1  - 19-23 March 2011
AB  - Virtual Reality (VR) systems cannot be promoted for complex applications (involving the interpretation of massive and intricate databases) without creating natural and ”transparent” user interfaces: intuitive interfaces are required to bring non-expert users to use VR technologies. Many studies have been carried out on multimodal and collaborative systems in VR. Although these two aspects are usually studied separately, they share interesting similarities. Our work focuses on the way to manage multimodal and collaborative interactions in a same process. We present here the similarities between these two processes and the main features of a reconfigurable multimodal and collaborative supervisor for Virtual Environments (VEs). The aim of such a system is to ensure the merge of pieces of information coming from VR devices (tracking, gestures, speech, haptics, etc.), to control immersive multi-user applications using the main communication and sensorimotor channels of humans. The framework's architecture of this supervisor wants to be generic, modular and reconfigurable (via an XML configuration file), in order to be applied to many different contexts.
